What this notebook will do¶

This notebook will try to estimate the power our kernel-density based overlap method has for a variety of effect sizes. This is not a post-hoc power analysis because I am not using the effect-size estimated from the data. There are good reasons not to do post-hoc power-analyses mainly because they do not really reveal the actual power of a test [1,2]. What I will do instead is to run a power analysis to see if the method could pick up the smallest reasonable effects for each parameter of interest.

Where to get the 'minimum detectable effects' from?¶

Luckily for us, we also have a previously published study (Fawcett et al. 2015)[3] on another rhinolophid's echolocation behaviour as single individuals and pairs. [3] will be used to set the minimum effect sizes, and calculate the power for these minimum effect sizes.

Our own effect sizes are likely to be different:¶

Despite the availability of this published study it is important to note that the effect sizes in our own study may actually be different because of 1) different study species 2) the fact that our study was done in the wild.

Fawcett et al. 2015 studied Rhinolophus capensis, which showed changes in their echolocation call behavious when flown with other bats. The fact that the species is different may have consequences on whether we can expect a similar reaction in the bats in our dataset, belonging to R. euryale and R. mehelyi. For instance, in our field site, the two rhinolophid species regularly fly together inside and outside the cave, forming groups of 2-10 individuals (pers obs.). I don't know if R. capensis shows such behaviour. If R. capensis is more of a solitary species, then we could expect stronger differences in the echolocation when individuals encounter other individuals.

Fawcett et al.2015 was a lab study, where individual bats and pairs of bats were flown together. It maybe the case that the flight room was a novel context for the bats flown in this study, and thus the changes in their echolocation behavious may reflect an over-amplification of the changes that they show in nature. Our study on the other hand is of bats echolocating in the field. The cave in which the recordings were made is a familiar space frequented by the bats on a daily basis. The familiarity of the cave volume might mean that individual bats may face less of a problem despite the loud calls from conspecifics. The bats in our study may thus show no or very low effect sizes in their echolocation call parameters.

Calculating 'power' and making the simulated data¶

The power is the rate at which the statistical test detects true positives. Here 'true positives' are those cases where the comparison of two groups is different by the minimum detectable effect (MDE). I will also implement simulated data where the two groups are from the same distribution to assess the rate of false positives.

For our particular case, the observed percentile of the two distributions is the measure of interest. When the distributions (single and multi bat call parameters) are similar, the overlap percentile will be relatively high (because the observed overlaps are close to the shuffled data overlaps). When the distributions are different, the observed percentiles will be low in comparison to the shuffld data overlaps. Thus the test 'detects' a difference when the observed overlap is low.

How much power is 'enough'?¶

Since this power analysis is being done after the experiments, and not before, the question is how will the resulting power calculations affect our interpretation of the data. We clearly cannot reject any tests which are lower than the typical 0.8 power threshold.

If we do see an effect in our final results, we need to weigh it with the observed power for those parameters. If we do not see differences between our single and multi bat groups, we need to understand how likely it is that the results are a true negative, or a false negative.

How much power is enough really depends on the consequences of the interpretation [4].In our case, it is better to have Type II (false negatives) results rather than Type 1 (false positives), and so even if our power is low - we could still gain a lot by reporting the results as they are. The fact that bats do not adjust their call parameters may actually be a point of discussion.

Setting the minimum expected effect sizes: what did Fawcett et al. 2015 find?¶

Luckily for us we have a previous publication with rhinolophid bats [3] which can inform us about the minimum expected effect sizes. Of course, Fawcett et al. 2015 [3] studied the echolocation changes in a different species, (Rhinolphus capensis) , and the actual effect sizes may actually be lower in our species. To avoid wild speculation, I'm just going to estimate effect sizes from [3], and then proceed to see what the power of our tests are.

  • ### No difference in (CF) peak frequency
  • ### 1.25-1.9 X increase in tFM duration in pairs
  • ### 0.74 X times shorter calls in pairs
  • ### lower minFM in FM sweeps. Drop in minimum frequency (-10dB) between 3-5 kHz
  • ### A drop in source level in pairs, but this could also be attributed to changes in beam shape for instance.

def include_measurement_accuracy(X, measurement_accuracy):
    '''
    '''
    return np.array([return_rounded_output(each, measurement_accuracy) for each in X])
        
def return_rounded_output(each, measurement_accuracy):
    remainder = np.remainder(each, measurement_accuracy)
    if remainder/measurement_accuracy < 0.5:
        return measurement_accuracy*int(each/measurement_accuracy)
    elif remainder/measurement_accuracy >=0.5:
        return measurement_accuracy*(int(each/measurement_accuracy)+1)
    
dB = lambda X : 20*np.log10(X)

In [7]:
def get_observed_percentiles(Ntrials, group1_data_gen, group2_data_gen, **kwargs):
    '''
    '''
    all_observed_percentiles = []
    for i in tqdm(range(Ntrials)):
        group1_data = group1_data_gen()
        group2_data = group2_data_gen()
        data_overlap, outputs, shuffled_overlaps = shuffle_overlap.overlap_w_shuffling(group1_data,
                                                                                       group2_data, **kwargs)
        observed_percentile = shuffle_overlap.percentile_score_of_value(data_overlap, shuffled_overlaps)
        all_observed_percentiles.append(observed_percentile)
    return all_observed_percentiles

        
def calculate_power_from_observed_percentiles(obs_percentiles, alpha):
    '''
    Parameters
    ----------
    obs_percentiles : list
        List with observed percentiles, which are floats between 0-100
    alpha : float > 0
        Alpha value or significance criterion.

    Returns
    -------
    power : float >0
    '''
    obs_pc = np.array(obs_percentiles)
    
    # get all values LEQ the alpha
    leq_alpha  = obs_pc <= alpha
    power  = sum(leq_alpha)/obs_pc.size

    return power



def power_and_true_negative_at_various_alphas(alpha, num_effect_sizes, all_observed_percentiles):
    """
    Parameters
    ----------
    alpha : list/array-like
        The various significance thresholds to be assesed
    num_effect_sizes : int>0
        The number of effects being simulated
    all_observed_percentiles : list
        List with floats containing the percentile run, which is the p-value equivalent. 
        The first set of num_trials p-values in the all_observed_percentiles is for the null-hypothesis
        The second set of num_trials p-values in the all_observed_percentiles corresponds to the 
        'effect' treatment. 
    Returns
    -------
    power_at_alpha : np.array
        Array with the power matrix. Each column corresponds to one effect size, and each row corresponds to one 
        significance threshold.

    """
    power_at_alpha = np.zeros((len(alpha), num_effect_sizes))

    obs_pctiles_split = np.array_split(all_observed_percentiles, num_effect_sizes)
    
    for j, each_pctile in enumerate(obs_pctiles_split):
        for i, sig_threshold in enumerate(alpha):
            true_positive_rate = calculate_power_from_observed_percentiles(each_pctile,
                                                                           sig_threshold)
            power_at_alpha[i, j] = true_positive_rate
    return power_at_alpha

def make_overview_plot(df, single, multi, colname):
    mean_colname = np.mean(df[colname])
    sd_colname = np.std(df[colname])
    plt.figure()
    plt.hist(df[colname], alpha=0.5, label=colname)
    plt.hist(single_bat[colname], alpha=0.5, label='single '+colname)
    plt.hist(multi_bat[colname], alpha=0.5, label='multi '+colname)
    plt.vlines(mean_colname, 0, 32)
    plt.text(mean_colname, 33, f'mean: {np.round(mean_colname, 5)}, \n sd: {np.round(sd_colname, 5)}')
    plt.legend()

Simulating the CF peak frequency data¶

Overall, the CF peak frequency distribution looks pretty unimodal and doesn't seem to differ across the group sizes. The worst case frequency resolution is at 200 Hz (ignoring the few outliers at 600 Hz). Let's use this information to create the simulated data for the power analysis.¶

We will not be including separate modelling of Doppler shifts because the analysed CF peak frequencies already result from a variety of emitted CFs and bat flight speeds.¶

Large effects like that in Fawcett et al. 2015 would have

Picking up changes in CF rms between single and multiple bat contexts¶

  • Fawcett et al. 2015 found a reduction in call source levels when R. capensis pairs were flown, in comparison to when the bats were flying alone. The difference in source levels was 15dB.
  • Here I will check a range of effect sizes, ranging from 0 to 15dB increase in source levels. Of course, it is important to remember that we actually have received levels in our study. However, given the fact that the volume remains the same, a shift in source level, will lead to a shift in the received level too. Thus an increase in source level by X dB will lead to approximately the same amount of shift in received levels too.
  • Here we simulate the case where multiple bats increase their source levels. This is because the general pattern for bats when faced with noise or conspecifics is to increase their source levels [REFS]

Summary CF received level :¶

$\frac{iFM}{CF}$ ratio¶

The $\frac{iFM}{CF}$ and $\frac{tFM}{CF}$ ratio as reported in Tian & Schintzler 1997 [5] is used to highlight the change in intensity of the two parts. For instance, as a R. ferrumequinum reaches the target, the $\frac{tFM}{CF}$ dB ratio increases - which indicates that the tFM component is getting louder than the CF.

Tian & Schnitzler 1997 report ratios between ~-12 to +10. We have similar values too. Overall, in the data, there is no obvious indication of any systematic change, but we can at least see if had there been any change, would we have been able to see it?

cf_duration¶

I'm actually not sure what the best way to deal with this kind of distribution is, because it's somewhat left skewed. However, to keep things simple I will continue the practice of using the change relative to the mean of the distribution as I did with the tfm and ifm durations. The mean x change assumption worked well to simulate changes in call parameters for all others because they were normal-ish looking, and somewhat symmetrical around the mean. In this particular case however, the distribution is clearly left-skewed.

In [45]:
colname = 'cf_duration'
make_overview_plot(df, single_bat, multi_bat, colname)

mean_cf_durn = np.mean(df[colname])
sd_cf_durn = np.std(df[colname])

def cfdurn_solitary_bat():
    solitary_bat_pf = np.random.normal(mean_cf_durn, sd_cf_durn, single_sample_size) # in ms
    solitary_bat_pf = include_measurement_accuracy(solitary_bat_pf, fm_duration_accuracy)
    return solitary_bat_pf

def cfdurn_multi_bat():
    group_bat_pf = np.random.normal(mean_cf_durn*rel_change,sd_cf_durn, group_sample_size) # in ms
    group_bat_pf = include_measurement_accuracy(group_bat_pf, fm_duration_accuracy)
    return group_bat_pf

tfm terminal frequency¶

Fawcett et al. 2015 found at drop of between 3-5 kHz in the -10 dB frequency in the i and t FM parts of the calls.
